{"id": "14436", "revid": "43671602", "url": "https://divinity.fandom.com/wiki?curid=14436", "title": "Cranley Huwbert", "text": " is a &lt;a href=\"Original%20Sin%20characters\"&gt;human&lt;/a&gt; residing in his &lt;a href=\"The%20Loremaster%27s%20House\"&gt;house&lt;/a&gt; in &lt;a href=\"Arx\"&gt;Arx&lt;/a&gt; in 1242 AD.\nBackground.\nCranley Huwbert is a scholar, loremaster and author. He resides in a relatively smaller estate in the eastern part of &lt;a href=\"Arx\"&gt;Arx&lt;/a&gt;. His books are widespread and presumably have accumulated plenty of readers.\nSome of Cranley's known idiosyncrasies are being disturbed enough by &lt;a href=\"Necromancer%20%28Original%20Sin%202%29\"&gt;necromancy&lt;/a&gt; that his handwriting became unusual when describing how acts of it are performed by a necromancer, as well as being biased in favour of &lt;a href=\"humans\"&gt;humans&lt;/a&gt;. \nHis home features an access to a large cellar in which he does a large share of his work because he believes his mind functions better in the dark. His hitherto unsuccessful attempts at poetry can be found lying around on the desks there."}
{"id": "13531", "revid": "49426621", "url": "https://divinity.fandom.com/wiki?curid=13531", "title": "Crawler", "text": "Crawler is a 4th rank assassin stalking &lt;a href=\"Richard%20%28Divine%20Divinity%29\"&gt;Richard&lt;/a&gt; in &lt;a href=\"The%20Farmlands\"&gt;The Farmlands&lt;/a&gt;.\nBackground.\nCrawler is a backstabber (4th rank assassin) of the &lt;a href=\"Assassin%27s%20Guild\"&gt;Assassin's Guild&lt;/a&gt; and as such a master stalker when it comes to tracking his prey. He likes to gloat over his victims before killing them, which has allowed his current target, Sir Richard, to escape twice.\nInteractions with the player character.\nHe asks &lt;a href=\"Lucian\"&gt;Lucian&lt;/a&gt; to leave him alone when encountered. After Lucian met Richard, Crawler will ask the latter's location. Regardless of Lucian's answer, he will attack."}
{"id": "9792", "revid": "31775388", "url": "https://divinity.fandom.com/wiki?curid=9792", "title": "Crawling Infestation (DOS EE)", "text": "Description.\nCan only be used once per combat.\nPlant a monstrous egg in a nearby target.\nUnless the target resists or succeeds a saving throw using Constitution, its mortal shell will give way to a monster as it comes out after 3 turns."}
{"id": "3491", "revid": "49135869", "url": "https://divinity.fandom.com/wiki?curid=3491", "title": "Creature (Undead)", "text": "A Creature is a type of &lt;a href=\"undead\"&gt;undead&lt;/a&gt; minion, commonly used as a &lt;a href=\"Necromancer\"&gt;Necromancer&lt;/a&gt;'s pet or as an ally in battle. It is created by stitching together limbs taken from a variety of species.\nGameplay.\nThere are 2 kinds of creatures in , enemy creatures, and the player's creature.\nEnemy Creatures are rare but dangerous, often appearing in groups of various roles.\nThe Player's Creature is a unique ally that can be summoned by using a &lt;a href=\"Crystal%20Skull\"&gt;Crystal Skull&lt;/a&gt;. Unlike other summons, Creatures last indefinitely until they are either killed or unsummoned. Creatures are also unaffected by the skill &lt;a href=\"Summon%20Mastery\"&gt;Summon Mastery&lt;/a&gt;.\nThe Creature begins with a default set of low-quality &lt;a href=\"Creature%20Parts\"&gt;limbs&lt;/a&gt;. New limbs of varying quality can be dropped rarely from the corresponding enemy, but can also be found in chests or be purchased from specialized limb vendors.\nA creature's limbs can be swapped out at a &lt;a href=\"Necromancer\"&gt;Necromancer&lt;/a&gt; in order to modify its stats and &lt;a href=\"Skills%20%28Dragon%20Knight%20Saga%29\"&gt;skills&lt;/a&gt;, allowing the player to customize their Creature to suit whatever role is needed.\nAfter the Creature is destroyed, it takes 60 seconds before it can be summoned again."}
{"id": "2595", "revid": "27868532", "url": "https://divinity.fandom.com/wiki?curid=2595", "title": "Creature Parts", "text": "Creature Parts are used to build the player's &lt;a href=\"Creature%20%28Undead%29\"&gt;Creature&lt;/a&gt; and come in four types; Head, Torso, Arms and Legs.\nThe parts can be changed by visiting a &lt;a href=\"Necromancer\"&gt;Necromancer&lt;/a&gt;.\nGameplay.\nCreature Parts have different quality levels, with Perfect being the best, and Rotten the worst.\nThe quality of a limb denotes how high the skills or stat bonuses of that limb are.\nA Creature's class is dependent on the head that it has. Each class behaves slightly differently in battle but all creatures, regardless of class, possess a melee attack."}
{"id": "8367", "revid": "31775388", "url": "https://divinity.fandom.com/wiki?curid=8367", "title": "Creature Training Notes", "text": "Creature Training Notes are &lt;a href=\"Books%20and%20notes%20%28Dragon%20Knight%20Saga%29\"&gt;notes&lt;/a&gt; in \"\".\nDescription.\nCreature training notes are found in the \"Inner Passage\" of &lt;a href=\"Stone%27s%20Flying%20Fortress\"&gt;Stone's Flying Fortress&lt;/a&gt; in the &lt;a href=\"Orobas%20Fjords\"&gt;Orobas Fjords&lt;/a&gt;, presumably dictated by the &lt;a href=\"necromancer\"&gt;necromancer&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Xanlosch\"&gt;Xanlosch&lt;/a&gt; while feeding his pet creature &lt;a href=\"Isabelle\"&gt;Isabelle&lt;/a&gt;."}
{"id": "2103", "revid": "43671602", "url": "https://divinity.fandom.com/wiki?curid=2103", "title": "Creatures", "text": "Species.\nIn &lt;a href=\"Rivellon\"&gt;Rivellon&lt;/a&gt;, there are literally hundreds of different creatures, all sorted into species, level and class (example, level 11 Lesser Skeleton Mage). These species include humanoids, demons, undead and many others, though the most common species in Rivellon appear to be the goblins and skeletons.\nClasses.\nEnemy races include summoners, &lt;a href=\"necromancer\"&gt;necromancer&lt;/a&gt;s, captains, sergeants, etc. Each enemy class is unique, though some higher ranking Black Ring soldiers such as Captains are multi-classed.\nThe Summoners are the same as necromancers, though instead of undead creatures such as skeletons, they often produce the same race as the summoner, but they are slightly weaker. Summoned enemies do not give experience or loot bags.\nCaptains only exist in 3 species, Black ring soldiers, Bandits and Dragon elves, Captains are usually a cross between Mages and Warriors, but in some, such as Bandits, they may be a cross of Rangers and Warriors.\nMages are wizards, specializing into magical attacks, a tip to beating them is to get close to them, as most run away to a range so they may cast another spell.\nWarriors only use swords, axes or shields in the form of melee attacks, but do not think that jumping on top of a block of concrete or ruins is going to protect you as they may also cast spells when you are far away or out of their accessible areas.\nRangers are fully-ranged units that shoot from afar, only ever staying at a distance and running away when you draw too close; Bandit rangers and other species may also use poison or stun arrows.\nHealers are similar to mages but can heal their comrades and use weaker magical attacks.\nClass list:"}
