{"id": "15197", "revid": "43671602", "url": "https://divinity.fandom.com/wiki?curid=15197", "title": "Death Strike", "text": " is a &lt;a href=\"Divine%20Divinity%20skills%23Way%20of%20the%20warrior\"&gt;Warrior skill&lt;/a&gt; in \"&lt;a href=\"Divine%20Divinity\"&gt;Divine Divinity&lt;/a&gt;\".\nDescription.\nDeath Strike is a passive skill that grants Lucian a small chance to instantly kill an enemy upon melee strike. Enemies may resist the instant death if their spiritual resistance is high enough. Since it is a passive skill it is always active and does not cost any magic or stamina. There is a spell version of this skill called &lt;a href=\"Divine%20Death\"&gt;Divine Death&lt;/a&gt; that can be learnt upon ascending to Divinity as part of the quest &lt;a href=\"Begin%20the%20Blessing%20Ritual\"&gt;Begin the Blessing Ritual&lt;/a&gt;. Unlike this skill however, the spell will always instantly kill an enemy if their spiritual resistance isnt high enough."}
{"id": "12373", "revid": "43671602", "url": "https://divinity.fandom.com/wiki?curid=12373", "title": "Death Wish", "text": " is a &lt;a href=\"Necromancer%20%28Original%20Sin%202%29\"&gt;novice Necromancer&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Original%20Sin%202%20Skills\"&gt;skill&lt;/a&gt; in \"\".\nDescription.\nSkill.\n is a supportive necromancer skill that allows caster to boost damage of the target character (including hostile and neutral characters) in proportion to their lost Vitality for 2 turns. The damage bonus is equal to the percentage of lost Vitality. For example, a character with 30 % Vitality left will gain a + 70 % bonus to damage and a character with only 1 % Vitality left will receive 99 % bonus to damage done. This bonus is applied to damage itself and visible under damage attribute. \nNote however, that the actual bonus to damage varies between characters who rely on weapon-based skills and magic-based skills. The bonus provided by is categorised as a Miscellaneous bonus. As such, when dealing damage through skill based on weapon damage (ex. &lt;a href=\"Battle%20Stomp\"&gt;Battle Stomp&lt;/a&gt;) it will stack additively with weapon based damage, thus it will provide lesser damage boost than stated. For magic-based skills such as &lt;a href=\"Fireball%20%28Original%20Sin%202%29\"&gt;Fireball&lt;/a&gt;, the bonus is calculated multiplicatively and thus it truly provides stated bonus to damage. This bonus however does not apply to skills that tranfer or redirect damage such as &lt;a href=\"Original%20Sin%202%20Warfare\"&gt;warfare&lt;/a&gt; skill &lt;a href=\"Deflective%20Barrier\"&gt;Deflective Barrier&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=\"Original%20Sin%202%20Necromancer\"&gt;necromancer&lt;/a&gt; skill &lt;a href=\"Shackles%20of%20Pain\"&gt;Shackles of Pain&lt;/a&gt;.\nSince relies on &lt;a href=\"Necromancy\"&gt;Necromancy&lt;/a&gt; magic it cannot be cast if character is affected by &lt;a href=\"Silenced%20%28Status%29\"&gt;Silenced&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Enraged%20%28Status%29\"&gt;Enraged&lt;/a&gt; status effects.\nScroll and Skillbook.\n skillbook is a magical item that allows its reader to learn skill, if they have at least 2 points into &lt;a href=\"Original%20Sin%202%20Necromancer\"&gt;Necromancer&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Attributes%20and%20Abilities%20%28Original%20Sin%202%29\"&gt;ability&lt;/a&gt;, and use it indefinitely. In order to be able to cast the skill, character needs 1 free memory slot. Note that the book will disappear once read. The book weights 0.5 and its base value is 190 gold. Since is a novice Necromancer skill, traders will start selling the skillbook once &lt;a href=\"Godwoken\"&gt;Godwoken&lt;/a&gt; reach level 4.\n is one of the few magic-based skills in the game that does not have a scroll.\nSkill Modifiers.\n is a supportive skill that provides set bonus to damage as such this bonus itself cannot be modified through attributes, abilities and talents.\n skill itself can be modified through talents and other skills. \nLocations.\nTraders.\nFollowing table shows all NPCs who are guaranteed to sell necromancer spellbooks, with their location and coordinates in the right column, from them. The location shown in the table (and the coordinates) are only for the initial location the NPC is in. Note that some of these may have other spell/skillbooks and goods to sell. Out of these only \"&lt;a href=\"Tarquin\"&gt;Tarquin&lt;/a&gt;\" is guaranteed to follow the &lt;a href=\"Godwoken\"&gt;Godwoken&lt;/a&gt; as they travel with &lt;a href=\"The%20Lady%20Vengeance\"&gt;Lady Vengeance&lt;/a&gt;. \"&lt;a href=\"Jahan\"&gt;Jahan&lt;/a&gt;\" may join the Godwoken on the ship as well if his demands are met. "}
{"id": "2903", "revid": "27868532", "url": "https://divinity.fandom.com/wiki?curid=2903", "title": "Death of a Champion", "text": "Death of a Champion is a &lt;a href=\"Ego%20Draconis%20quests\"&gt;side quest&lt;/a&gt; issued by &lt;a href=\"Svadilfari\"&gt;Svadilfari&lt;/a&gt;, the leader of the &lt;a href=\"Red%20Hammer%20Tribe\"&gt;Red Hammer Tribe&lt;/a&gt; in \"\".\nDetailed Walkthrough.\nThis quest clashes with &lt;a href=\"A%20Shaman%27s%20Ransom\"&gt;A Shaman's Ransom&lt;/a&gt;. The Dragon Knight is forced to choose sides by either completing the quest for Svadilfari or Aurelius (by refusing this quest and slaying Svadilfari). If you aid the goblin leader, a fake, poisoned replica is given instead. &lt;a href=\"Aurelius\"&gt;Aurelius&lt;/a&gt; does not notice the swap and as soon as he lays his hands on it, dies from the noxious poison of the fake trophy.\nWhen you return to cave, you find &lt;a href=\"Svadilfari\"&gt;Svadilfari&lt;/a&gt; ungrateful and ready to cut down his benefactor as you are no longer needed. When his health gets low, &lt;a href=\"Svadilfari\"&gt;Svadilfari&lt;/a&gt; will flee outside. Resume the fight with the renegade goblin leader in air.\nThe tactics do not differ from occasional winged bosses. The reward is an additional option."}
{"id": "13981", "revid": "27868532", "url": "https://divinity.fandom.com/wiki?curid=13981", "title": "Deathblow", "text": " is a &lt;a href=\"Divine%20Divinity%20Weapons\"&gt;unique hammer&lt;/a&gt; in \"&lt;a href=\"Divine%20Divinity\"&gt;Divine Divinity&lt;/a&gt;\".\nCharacteristics.\nA two-handed hammer that requires physical strength to wield, it boosts both &lt;a href=\"Intelligence\"&gt;Intelligence&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Vitality\"&gt;Vitality&lt;/a&gt; and can have two charms implanted within it.\nIt requires &lt;a href=\"Identify\"&gt;Identify&lt;/a&gt; (3) to identify it.\nLocation.\nFound in the &lt;a href=\"Cave%20%28Rivertown%20Market%29\"&gt;lich cave&lt;/a&gt; to the south east of &lt;a href=\"Rivertown%20Market\"&gt;Rivertown Market&lt;/a&gt;."}
{"id": "18455", "revid": "43671602", "url": "https://divinity.fandom.com/wiki?curid=18455", "title": "Deathfog", "text": "Deathfog is an extremely toxic substance that is capable of devastating organic life, and is heralded by some as 'the most lethal weapon of our time'.\nHistory.\nThe earliest known usage of Deathfog was by the &lt;a href=\"Divine%20Order\"&gt;Divine Order&lt;/a&gt; in 1233 AD during The Chaos War. Two &lt;a href=\"lizards\"&gt;lizards&lt;/a&gt; approached &lt;a href=\"Lucian\"&gt;Lucian the Divine&lt;/a&gt; with a plan to release deathfog in the Elven lands in an attempt to combat the &lt;a href=\"Black%20Ring\"&gt;Black Ring&lt;/a&gt;. Lucian, conflicted by the morality of the plan, sought council from &lt;a href=\"Ifan%20ben-Mezd\"&gt;Ifan ben-Mezd&lt;/a&gt;, who agreed to the plan under the stipulation that the &lt;a href=\"Elves\"&gt;Elves&lt;/a&gt; be evacuated before the deathfog was released. However, internal sabotage by &lt;a href=\"Alexandar\"&gt;Alexandar&lt;/a&gt;, Lucian's youngest son, caused the deathfog to be released prematurely, wiping out scores of elves and rendering their lands uninhabitable.\nRegardless, the deathfog successfully dealt significant losses to Black Ring forces. The deaths of so many elves to the deathfog weakened the Seven God &lt;a href=\"Tir-Cendelius\"&gt;Tir-Cendelius&lt;/a&gt;, unleashing the &lt;a href=\"voidwoken\"&gt;voidwoken&lt;/a&gt; and their leader the &lt;a href=\"God%20King\"&gt;God King&lt;/a&gt; from the &lt;a href=\"Void\"&gt;Void&lt;/a&gt;, who proceeded to take control of the weakened Ring forces.\nIn 1242 AD, a lizard known as &lt;a href=\"The%20Shadow%20Prince\"&gt;The Shadow Prince&lt;/a&gt; created a deathfog bomb which was to be used to kill &lt;a href=\"The%20Mother%20Tree\"&gt;The Mother Tree&lt;/a&gt;, an entity that the Shadow Prince believed would attempt to conquer the world.\nAfter the Divine's death, the morality of the use of deathfog by the Divine Order was questioned, as previously only the Divine himself determined when it was right to be used.\nBy 1300 AD, the Black Ring used deathfog to render the lands they conquered uninhabitable. Safe in their flying fortresses, the Black Ring's movements were unhindered by the toxic mists.\nAfter the &lt;a href=\"The%20Dragon%20Knight\"&gt;last Dragon Knight&lt;/a&gt; claimed the &lt;a href=\"Battle%20Tower\"&gt;Battle Tower&lt;/a&gt; from the necromancer &lt;a href=\"Laiken\"&gt;Laiken&lt;/a&gt;, Damian, angered by the Knight's continued defiance, laid siege to &lt;a href=\"Sentinel%20Island\"&gt;Sentinel Island&lt;/a&gt;, deploying a Flying Fortress and covering the land with deathfog. Damian then unleashed the Black Ring upon &lt;a href=\"Broken%20Valley\"&gt;Broken Valley&lt;/a&gt;, personally seeing to the destruction of &lt;a href=\"Broken%20Valley%20Village\"&gt;Broken Valley Village&lt;/a&gt; and releasing deathfog across the entire region."}
